{"title_page": "WPHI-FM", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=July 2016}}\n{{Infobox radio station\n| name               = WPHI-FM\n| image              =\n| city               = [[Jenkintown, Pennsylvania]]\n| area               = [[Delaware Valley|Greater Philadelphia (Delaware Valley)]]\n| branding           = ''Hip Hop 103.9''\n| slogan             = We The Culture\n| frequency          = 103.9 [[hertz|MHz]] {{HD Radio}}\n| translator         =\n| repeater           = 100.3 [[hertz|MHz]] [[WRNB]]-HD2\n| airdate            = {{start date|1960|11|01}} )as WIBF-FM)\n| format             = [[Urban contemporary]]\n| language           = [[English language|English]]\n| erp                = 270 [[watt]]s (analog)<br>10 [[watt]]s (digital)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/forms/prod/prefill_and_display.pl?Application_id=1416331&Service=FD&Form_id=335&Facility_id=30572 |title=FCC 335-FM Digital Notification [WPHI-FM] |date=February 18, 2011 |website=fcc.gov |publisher=[[Federal Communications Commission]] |access-date=2018-05-10}}</ref>\n| haat               = {{convert|338|m|sp=us}}\n| class              = A\n| facility_id        = 30572\n| coordinates        = {{coord|40|02|29.6|N|75|14|11.4|W|region:US-PA_type:landmark_region:US_source:FCC}} ([[North American Datum#North American Datum of 1927|NAD27]])\n| callsign_meaning   ='''W''' '''PHI'''ladelphia \n| former_callsigns   = WIBF(-FM) (1960\u20131992)<br>WDRE (1992\u20131997)<br>WPPZ-FM (2005\u20132016)\n| former_frequencies =\n| affiliations       =\n| owner              = [[Urban One]]\n| licensee           = Radio One Licenses, LLC\n| sister_stations    = [[WPPZ-FM]], [[WRNB]]\n| webcast            = [https://1039hiphop.com/listen-live/ Listen Live]\n| website            = [https://1039hiphop.com 1039hiphop.com]\n}}\n\n'''WPHI-FM''' (103.9 [[FM broadcasting|FM]], \"Hip Hop 103.9\") is a [[commercial radio|commercial]] [[FM radio|FM]] [[radio station]] [[city of license|licensed]] to serve [[Jenkintown, Pennsylvania]]. The station is owned by [[Urban One]] through licensee Radio One Licenses, LLC and broadcasts an [[urban contemporary]] format. Studios are located in [[Bala Cynwyd, Pennsylvania|Bala Cynwyd]], and the broadcast tower used by the station is located in the Roxborough section of [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania|Philadelphia]] at ({{coord|40|02|30.1|N|75|14|10.1|W}}).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://transition.fcc.gov/fcc-bin/fmq?call=WPHI |title=FM Query Results for WPHI-FM |website=fcc.gov |publisher=[[Federal Communications Commission]] |accessdate=2018-05-10}}</ref> The station has always been short-spaced due to adjacent channel interference from [[WMGM (FM)|WMGM]] in [[Atlantic City]], [[WXCY]] in [[Havre de Grace, Maryland]], and [[WNNJ]] in [[Newton, New Jersey]] (all located on 103.7 FM), [[WAEB-FM]] in [[Allentown, Pennsylvania|Allentown]] and [[WNNK]] in [[Harrisburg, Pennsylvania|Harrisburg]] (both located on 104.1 FM), as well as [[WRFF]] (104.5 FM), and co-channel interference from [[WRCN]] on [[Long Island]] and [[WNBM]] in [[Bronxville, New York]]. As such, the station broadcasts at only 270 watts, making it the weakest station broadcasting from the Roxborough tower farm.\n\n==History==\n===WIBF-FM===\n103.9 originally started out on November 1, 1960 as '''WIBF-FM''', which was owned by Fox Broadcasting, not related to the more recent [[Fox Broadcasting Company]] television network.  The call letters stood for the station's owners &mdash; brothers William and Irwin Fox and their father Benjamin Fox, a local real estate developer.\n\nIn the 1960s and 1970s, the station featured a format of [[Middle of the road (music)|MOR]], [[big bands]], [[Dixieland jazz]] and the area's first FM [[country music]] show, plus religious and ethnic programs.  By the mid-1970s, the station switched to religious and ethnic programming during the day and Spanish music at night. The [[Barry Reisman]] Show, featuring Jewish music and programming, was broadcast during the afternoon [[drive time]] from 1969 through the station's sale in 1992.  In 1965, the station picked up a television sister in WIBF-TV, channel 29 (now [[WTXF-TV]], a station coincidentally owned by the Fox Broadcasting Company).\n\n===WDRE===\n[[Image:WDRE.JPG|right|164px|103.9 WDRE logo]] <!-- 328/2 -->\n{{unreferenced section|date=February 2010}}\nThe station sold by the Fox family in October 1992 by Jarad Broadcasting, and on November 9, 1992, at Midnight, WDRE from [[Garden City, New York]] started [[simulcasting]] its programming with WIBF-FM, and shortly after the simulcast began, WIBF's branding was changed to \"103.9 WDRE\" to match the New York station. The simulcasting was part of a large effort by Jarad called \"The Underground Network\", a network consisting of seven stations from across the country simulcasting WDRE. In 1995, the network ceased operations, WDRE in New York would change its call letters back to [[WLIR]], and made WIBF-FM in Philadelphia an independent, local modern rock station; WIBF-FM then changed its own callsign to '''WDRE''' - \"'''W'''e '''D'''a'''RE''' to be Different\" - to match its branding.\n\nWDRE was branded as \"Philly's Modern Rock\". \"[[Alive (Pearl Jam song)|Alive]]\" by [[Pearl Jam]] was the first song played on WDRE.<ref>[http://formatchange.com/1039-wibf-flips-from-ethnic-to-modern-rock/  WIBF Flips from Ethnic to Modern Rock]</ref>\n\nThe station helped launch the careers of many famous [[disc jockey]]s and local personalities.  They include [[Preston Elliot]] and [[Steve Morrison (radio personality)|Steve Morrison]] of the [[Preston and Steve]] morning show on [[WMMR]], Bret Hamilton of [[WCAU-TV]], Marilyn Russell (formerly of [[WXPN-HD2|Y100]], [[WXPN]], [[WMGK]], now on [[WOGL]]), [[Jim McGuinn]] (also known as Rumor Boy), the former Program Director of [[WRNB|WPLY]] (now currently programming [[KCMP]] in the [[Twin Cities]]), and Mel \"Toxic\" Taylor, who went on to [[WIP-FM|WYSP]].\n\nVeteran DJ Mel \"Toxic\" Taylor (formerly of WPST and [[WXTU#I-92.2FStudio 92|WIFI]]) was the first DJ hired for the only 2 local shows that would be live from Philadelphia each week.\n\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[Image:DREgional.JPG|thumb|200px|right|WDRE's local Modern Rock [[compact disc|CD]], ''DREgional Volume 1'']] -->\nWhen WDRE Philadelphia became a local radio station in 1995, talent was hired from within the city (e.g. Bret Hamilton, formerly of [[WIOQ]]) and outside of the city.  While WDRE never became a true mainstream radio station in the Philadelphia radio market due to its weak signal, the station gained a cult status in the Philadelphia area, and as a result, events like the station's music festival (known as \"DREfest\") sold out to a crowd of over 25,000 people.\n\nHowever, in December 1996, [[Radio One (company)|Radio One]] bought WDRE from Jarad, and on the 16th of that month, WDRE announced that the station would flip to a then-undisclosed format in February 1997.<ref>[http://formatchange.com/wdre-announces-pending-format-change/  WDRE Announces Pending Format Change]</ref><ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OZvhyQw6ZPk</ref>\n\nDue to the informed notice of the station's flip, the staff at WDRE were able to organize a concert called \"Bitterfest\", which was to be held at The Electric Factory.  The concert featured local acts [[G Love]] and the [[Fun Lovin' Criminals]], and was created to celebrate the life of WDRE as a local institution for modern rock.  On February 7, 1997, \"Bitterfest\" was held to a sold-out crowd of over 3,000 people, with all of the WDRE staff present at the event.  At Midnight on February 8, 1997, as the crowd at Bitterfest chanted \"'D-R-E! 'D-R-E! 'D-R-E!\", a lucky (or unlucky) listener was selected to \"pull the plug\" on WDRE, with the station ending with the first song that started the format: [[Pearl Jam]]'s \"[[Alive (Pearl Jam song)|Alive]]\".<ref>[http://formatchange.com/1039-wdre-flips-from-modern-rock-to-urban/  WDRE Flips from Modern Rock to Urban]</ref> Two of the WDRE disc jockeys (Preston Eliot, Bret Hamilton) went to [[WRNB|Y100]], as did 'DRE Program Director Jim McGuinn, and midday and Sunday night DJ Marilyn Russell (as Promotions Director for Y100). Y100 was also bought out by [[Radio One (company)|Radio One]] in 2000, and flipped in 2005 to [[urban contemporary]].\n\n====WDRE on-air schedule====\n\n=====Weekdays=====\n*Mornings: \n**January&mdash;September 1996: ''The WDRE Morning Show'' with Sarah, Spike and Brian\n**September 1996&mdash;February 1997: ''The WDRE Morning Show'' with Sarah, Spike and Vinnie\n*Middays: Bret Hamilton\n*Afternoons: Preston Elliot\n*Evenings: John Castino\n*Overnights: Leigh Taylor\n\n=====Weekends=====\n*Sunday Evenings: Marilyn Russell\n*Sunday Overnights: Dan Fein\n*Various Shifts: Brian Robbins\n*Various Shifts: Debbie Mann (formerly of [[WXPN]] 88.5 and [[WRNR-FM]] 103.1 Annapolis, Maryland)\n*Various Shifts: Gil Edwards\n*Various Shifts: Rumor Boy (Jim McGuinn)\n*Various Shifts: Chris Martin\n\n===WPHI-FM then WPPZ-FM and back again===\nOn February 10, 1997, after a weekend of [[stunting (broadcasting)|stunting]] with [[classic soul]] music, the station flipped to [[Urban Contemporary]], branded as \"Philly 103.9.\"<ref>http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-RandR/1990s/1997/RR-1997-02-14.pdf</ref> The call letters were soon changed to '''WPHI'''. When the station rebranded as '''The Beat''' in April 2002, it shifted to [[rhythmic top 40]].<ref>http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-RandR/2000s/2002/RR-2002-04-26.pdf</ref> By [[2006 in radio|2006]], [[Radio & Records]]/[[Nielsen BDS]] moved it to the [[urban contemporary]] panel, but [[Mediabase]] followed suit in [[2011 in radio|2011]], completing the rhythmic to urban shift.\n\n[[File:WPPZ.png|thumb|logo as Praise, 2005-2016]]\nOn February 27, 2005, [[Radio One (company)|Radio One]] moved the \"Beat\" format to the 100.3 frequency, which was formerly [[Y-Rock On XPN|Y100]]. 103.9 then flipped to [[urban gospel]], branded as \"Praise 103.9\".<ref>https://mycitypaper.com/articles/2005-03-31/cover.shtml</ref> The callsign was changed to '''WPPZ-FM''' on March 3.\n\nExcept for \"The [[Yolanda Adams]] Morning Show\" and CeCe McGhee weekday afternoons, the station ran jockless throughout the day until August 2007. In late August, the addition of performer Lonnie Hunter from Chicago was made to be the mid-day personality along with Sheik Meah. Famous speaker Les Brown was also added to be on Sunday nights from 7&ndash;9pm. In September, Pastor Alan E. Waller joined the staff to do a Saturday morning show from 10&ndash;11am and two more weekend shows were added. The \"Holy Hip-Hop Show\" was added on Saturday nights from 7&ndash;9pm and a Christian dating show was added on Sundays from 9&ndash;11pm.\n\nWPPZ's current staff includes Lonnie Hunter, Brother Marcus, and CeCe Magee. Former DJs include Church Lady (2007&ndash;2008), Ed Long (2005&ndash;2007), CoCo Brother (2011&ndash;2013), and Les Brown and B.I.G. C.I.T.Y. (2008&ndash;2009; 2009&ndash;present).\n\nOn September 27, 2016, at Midnight, WPPZ and WPHI swapped frequencies, with \"Praise\" moving to 107.9 FM, and \"Boom\" moving to 103.9 FM (it also marked the return of the WPHI call letters to the frequency that originated the call letters). With the change, WPHI's [[classic hip hop]] format shifted to urban contemporary; the classic hip hop songs have been reduced to just a few per hour, with the station now emphasizing currents and recurrents. This marks the fourth attempt by Radio One to compete against long dominant [[WUSL]].<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/108389/boom-praise-swap-locations-in-philadelphia/ Boom 103.9 Philadelphia Segues To Urban Hot AC On New Frequency]</ref>\n\nEight months after WPHI's format switch, [[WISX]] flipped to a classic hip hop-leaning [[rhythmic AC]] on June 30, 2017.\n\nOn December 24, 2019, WPHI rebranded as \"Hip Hop 103.9\".<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/182584/wphi-rebrands-as-hip-hop-103-9/ WPHI Rebrands as Hip Hop 103.9] Radioinsight - December 24, 2019</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[WLIR]] \u2014 the original \"WDRE\" from 1987 to 1996, at 92.7 FM in Garden City, New York\n*[[WXPN-HD2]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{no footnotes|remainder of this section|date=February 2010}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.boomphilly.com/ Boom Philly] &mdash; official WPHI-FM website\n*{{FM station data|WPHI}}\n\n===WDRE era===\n<!-- looks like many of these could be used as references also -->\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bZ9-ELstmjk \"103.9 WDRE Philadelphia, The Birth 1992\"] &mdash; studio footage of \"WIBF\" format to \"WDRE\" format switch at midnight; press parties, including a press event with [[Joey Ramone]]; photos of staff and guests\n*[http://www.xpn.org/yrock-on-xpn/archives/wdre-reunion WDRE Reunion] &mdash; articles and footage about WDRE on the University of Pennsylvania [[WXPN]] website\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20010502162822/http://www.djchas.com/wdrephilly/ WDRE 103.9 FM] &mdash; archived copy of the original WDRE website\n*{{cite news | url = http://citypaper.net/articles/011598/om1.shtml | title = Mourning Show | first = Frank | last = Lewis | work = [[Philadelphia City Paper]] | date = January 15\u201322, 1998 | location = [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]] | access-date = 2010-02-15 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090903192628/http://www.citypaper.net/articles/011598/om1.shtml | archive-date = 2009-09-03 | url-status = dead }} &mdash; follow-up on WDRE popularity after end of format\n*{{cite web | url = http://citypaper.net/articles/013097/article027.shtml | title = Rock On, Please | first = Katherine | last = Kalavritinos | work = [[Philadelphia City Paper]] | date = January 30 \u2013 February 6, 1997 | location = [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]] | access-date = February 15, 2010 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20020917151611/http://citypaper.net/articles/013097/article027.shtml | archive-date = September 17, 2002 | url-status = dead | df = mdy-all }} &mdash; short letter to the editor with WDRE end date given\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090506072710/http://www.angelfire.com/nj2/piratejim/phillyfmhistory2.html Philadelphia FM Radio History] &mdash; timeline of 103.9 <!-- credits sources, and appears to be a source for a some of the text in the article -->\n*[http://www.angelfire.com/nj/NirvanaRulz/wdre/wdre.html 103.9 WDRE...Philly's Modern Rock] &mdash; page on Angelfire, with DJ locations\n\n{{Philadelphia Radio}}\n{{Urban Radio Stations in Pennsylvania}}\n{{Radio One}}\n\n{{coord|40.0416|N|75.2365|W|type:landmark_region:US_source:FCC|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Radio stations established in 1960]]\n[[Category:Urban One stations]]\n[[Category:Radio stations in Philadelphia|PHI-FM]]\n[[Category:1960 establishments in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Urban contemporary radio stations in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{more citations needed|date=July 2016}}\n{{Infobox radio station\n| name               = WPHI-FM\n| image              =\n| city               = [[Jenkintown, Pennsylvania]]\n| area               = [[Delaware Valley|Greater Philadelphia (Delaware Valley)]]\n| branding           = ''Hip Hop 103.9''\n| slogan             = We The Culture\n| frequency          = 103.9 [[hertz|MHz]] {{HD Radio}}\n| translator         =\n| repeater           = 100.3 [[hertz|MHz]] [[WRNB]]-HD2\n| airdate            = {{start date|1960|11|01}} )as WIBF-FM)\n| format             = [[Urban Contemporary]]\n| language           = [[English language|English]]\n| erp                = 270 [[watt]]s (analog)<br>10 [[watt]]s (digital)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/forms/prod/prefill_and_display.pl?Application_id=1416331&Service=FD&Form_id=335&Facility_id=30572 |title=FCC 335-FM Digital Notification [WPHI-FM] |date=February 18, 2011 |website=fcc.gov |publisher=[[Federal Communications Commission]] |access-date=2018-05-10}}</ref>\n| haat               = {{convert|338|m|sp=us}}\n| class              = A\n| facility_id        = 30572\n| coordinates        = {{coord|40|02|29.6|N|75|14|11.4|W|region:US-PA_type:landmark_region:US_source:FCC}} ([[North American Datum#North American Datum of 1927|NAD27]])\n| callsign_meaning   ='''W''' '''PHI'''ladelphia \n| former_callsigns   = WIBF(-FM) (1960\u20131992)<br>WDRE (1992\u20131997)<br>WPPZ-FM (2005\u20132016)\n| former_frequencies =\n| affiliations       =\n| owner              = [[Urban One]]\n| licensee           = Radio One Licenses, LLC\n| sister_stations    = [[WPPZ-FM]], [[WRNB]]\n| webcast            = [https://1039hiphop.com/listen-live/ Listen Live]\n| website            = [https://1039hiphop.com 1039hiphop.com]\n}}\n\n'''WPHI-FM''' (103.9 [[FM broadcasting|FM]], \"Hip Hop 103.9\") is a [[commercial radio|commercial]] [[FM radio|FM]] [[radio station]] [[city of license|licensed]] to serve [[Jenkintown, Pennsylvania]]. The station is owned by [[Urban One]] through licensee Radio One Licenses, LLC and broadcasts an [[urban contemporary]] format. Studios are located in [[Bala Cynwyd, Pennsylvania|Bala Cynwyd]], and the broadcast tower used by the station is located in the Roxborough section of [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania|Philadelphia]] at ({{coord|40|02|30.1|N|75|14|10.1|W}}).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://transition.fcc.gov/fcc-bin/fmq?call=WPHI |title=FM Query Results for WPHI-FM |website=fcc.gov |publisher=[[Federal Communications Commission]] |accessdate=2018-05-10}}</ref> The station has always been short-spaced due to adjacent channel interference from [[WMGM (FM)|WMGM]] in [[Atlantic City]], [[WXCY]] in [[Havre de Grace, Maryland]], and [[WNNJ]] in [[Newton, New Jersey]] (all located on 103.7 FM), [[WAEB-FM]] in [[Allentown, Pennsylvania|Allentown]] and [[WNNK]] in [[Harrisburg, Pennsylvania|Harrisburg]] (both located on 104.1 FM), as well as [[WRFF]] (104.5 FM), and co-channel interference from [[WRCN]] on [[Long Island]] and [[WNBM]] in [[Bronxville, New York]]. As such, the station broadcasts at only 270 watts, making it the weakest station broadcasting from the Roxborough tower farm.\n\n==History==\n===WIBF-FM===\n103.9 originally started out on November 1, 1960 as '''WIBF-FM''', which was owned by Fox Broadcasting, not related to the more recent [[Fox Broadcasting Company]] television network.  The call letters stood for the station's owners &mdash; brothers William and Irwin Fox and their father Benjamin Fox, a local real estate developer.\n\nIn the 1960s and 1970s, the station featured a format of [[Middle of the road (music)|MOR]], [[big bands]], [[Dixieland jazz]] and the area's first FM [[country music]] show, plus religious and ethnic programs.  By the mid-1970s, the station switched to religious and ethnic programming during the day and Spanish music at night. The [[Barry Reisman]] Show, featuring Jewish music and programming, was broadcast during the afternoon [[drive time]] from 1969 through the station's sale in 1992.  In 1965, the station picked up a television sister in WIBF-TV, channel 29 (now [[WTXF-TV]], a station coincidentally owned by the Fox Broadcasting Company).\n\n===WDRE===\n[[Image:WDRE.JPG|right|164px|103.9 WDRE logo]] <!-- 328/2 -->\n{{unreferenced section|date=February 2010}}\nThe station sold by the Fox family in October 1992 by Jarad Broadcasting, and on November 9, 1992, at Midnight, WDRE from [[Garden City, New York]] started [[simulcasting]] its programming with WIBF-FM, and shortly after the simulcast began, WIBF's branding was changed to \"103.9 WDRE\" to match the New York station. The simulcasting was part of a large effort by Jarad called \"The Underground Network\", a network consisting of seven stations from across the country simulcasting WDRE. In 1995, the network ceased operations, WDRE in New York would change its call letters back to [[WLIR]], and made WIBF-FM in Philadelphia an independent, local modern rock station; WIBF-FM then changed its own callsign to '''WDRE''' - \"'''W'''e '''D'''a'''RE''' to be Different\" - to match its branding.\n\nWDRE was branded as \"Philly's Modern Rock\". \"[[Alive (Pearl Jam song)|Alive]]\" by [[Pearl Jam]] was the first song played on WDRE.<ref>[http://formatchange.com/1039-wibf-flips-from-ethnic-to-modern-rock/  WIBF Flips from Ethnic to Modern Rock]</ref>\n\nThe station helped launch the careers of many famous [[disc jockey]]s and local personalities.  They include [[Preston Elliot]] and [[Steve Morrison (radio personality)|Steve Morrison]] of the [[Preston and Steve]] morning show on [[WMMR]], Bret Hamilton of [[WCAU-TV]], Marilyn Russell (formerly of [[WXPN-HD2|Y100]], [[WXPN]], [[WMGK]], now on [[WOGL]]), [[Jim McGuinn]] (also known as Rumor Boy), the former Program Director of [[WRNB|WPLY]] (now currently programming [[KCMP]] in the [[Twin Cities]]), and Mel \"Toxic\" Taylor, who went on to [[WIP-FM|WYSP]].\n\nVeteran DJ Mel \"Toxic\" Taylor (formerly of WPST and [[WXTU#I-92.2FStudio 92|WIFI]]) was the first DJ hired for the only 2 local shows that would be live from Philadelphia each week.\n\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[Image:DREgional.JPG|thumb|200px|right|WDRE's local Modern Rock [[compact disc|CD]], ''DREgional Volume 1'']] -->\nWhen WDRE Philadelphia became a local radio station in 1995, talent was hired from within the city (e.g. Bret Hamilton, formerly of [[WIOQ]]) and outside of the city.  While WDRE never became a true mainstream radio station in the Philadelphia radio market due to its weak signal, the station gained a cult status in the Philadelphia area, and as a result, events like the station's music festival (known as \"DREfest\") sold out to a crowd of over 25,000 people.\n\nHowever, in December 1996, [[Radio One (company)|Radio One]] bought WDRE from Jarad, and on the 16th of that month, WDRE announced that the station would flip to a then-undisclosed format in February 1997.<ref>[http://formatchange.com/wdre-announces-pending-format-change/  WDRE Announces Pending Format Change]</ref><ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OZvhyQw6ZPk</ref>\n\nDue to the informed notice of the station's flip, the staff at WDRE were able to organize a concert called \"Bitterfest\", which was to be held at The Electric Factory.  The concert featured local acts [[G Love]] and the [[Fun Lovin' Criminals]], and was created to celebrate the life of WDRE as a local institution for modern rock.  On February 7, 1997, \"Bitterfest\" was held to a sold-out crowd of over 3,000 people, with all of the WDRE staff present at the event.  At Midnight on February 8, 1997, as the crowd at Bitterfest chanted \"'D-R-E! 'D-R-E! 'D-R-E!\", a lucky (or unlucky) listener was selected to \"pull the plug\" on WDRE, with the station ending with the first song that started the format: [[Pearl Jam]]'s \"[[Alive (Pearl Jam song)|Alive]]\".<ref>[http://formatchange.com/1039-wdre-flips-from-modern-rock-to-urban/  WDRE Flips from Modern Rock to Urban]</ref> Two of the WDRE disc jockeys (Preston Eliot, Bret Hamilton) went to [[WRNB|Y100]], as did 'DRE Program Director Jim McGuinn, and midday and Sunday night DJ Marilyn Russell (as Promotions Director for Y100). Y100 was also bought out by [[Radio One (company)|Radio One]] in 2000, and flipped in 2005 to [[urban contemporary]].\n\n====WDRE on-air schedule====\n\n=====Weekdays=====\n*Mornings: \n**January&mdash;September 1996: ''The WDRE Morning Show'' with Sarah, Spike and Brian\n**September 1996&mdash;February 1997: ''The WDRE Morning Show'' with Sarah, Spike and Vinnie\n*Middays: Bret Hamilton\n*Afternoons: Preston Elliot\n*Evenings: John Castino\n*Overnights: Leigh Taylor\n\n=====Weekends=====\n*Sunday Evenings: Marilyn Russell\n*Sunday Overnights: Dan Fein\n*Various Shifts: Brian Robbins\n*Various Shifts: Debbie Mann (formerly of [[WXPN]] 88.5 and [[WRNR-FM]] 103.1 Annapolis, Maryland)\n*Various Shifts: Gil Edwards\n*Various Shifts: Rumor Boy (Jim McGuinn)\n*Various Shifts: Chris Martin\n\n===WPHI-FM then WPPZ-FM and back again===\nOn February 10, 1997, after a weekend of [[stunting (broadcasting)|stunting]] with [[classic soul]] music, the station flipped to [[Urban Contemporary]], branded as \"Philly 103.9.\"<ref>http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-RandR/1990s/1997/RR-1997-02-14.pdf</ref> The call letters were soon changed to '''WPHI'''. When the station rebranded as '''The Beat''' in April 2002, it shifted to [[rhythmic top 40]].<ref>http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-RandR/2000s/2002/RR-2002-04-26.pdf</ref> By [[2006 in radio|2006]], [[Radio & Records]]/[[Nielsen BDS]] moved it to the [[urban contemporary]] panel, but [[Mediabase]] followed suit in [[2011 in radio|2011]], completing the rhythmic to urban shift.\n\n[[File:WPPZ.png|thumb|logo as Praise, 2005-2016]]\nOn February 27, 2005, [[Radio One (company)|Radio One]] moved the \"Beat\" format to the 100.3 frequency, which was formerly [[Y-Rock On XPN|Y100]]. 103.9 then flipped to [[urban gospel]], branded as \"Praise 103.9\".<ref>https://mycitypaper.com/articles/2005-03-31/cover.shtml</ref> The callsign was changed to '''WPPZ-FM''' on March 3.\n\nExcept for \"The [[Yolanda Adams]] Morning Show\" and CeCe McGhee weekday afternoons, the station ran jockless throughout the day until August 2007. In late August, the addition of performer Lonnie Hunter from Chicago was made to be the mid-day personality along with Sheik Meah. Famous speaker Les Brown was also added to be on Sunday nights from 7&ndash;9pm. In September, Pastor Alan E. Waller joined the staff to do a Saturday morning show from 10&ndash;11am and two more weekend shows were added. The \"Holy Hip-Hop Show\" was added on Saturday nights from 7&ndash;9pm and a Christian dating show was added on Sundays from 9&ndash;11pm.\n\nWPPZ's current staff includes Lonnie Hunter, Brother Marcus, and CeCe Magee. Former DJs include Church Lady (2007&ndash;2008), Ed Long (2005&ndash;2007), CoCo Brother (2011&ndash;2013), and Les Brown and B.I.G. C.I.T.Y. (2008&ndash;2009; 2009&ndash;present).\n\nOn September 27, 2016, at Midnight, WPPZ and WPHI swapped frequencies, with \"Praise\" moving to 107.9 FM, and \"Boom\" moving to 103.9 FM (it also marked the return of the WPHI call letters to the frequency that originated the call letters). With the change, WPHI's [[classic hip hop]] format shifted to urban contemporary; the classic hip hop songs have been reduced to just a few per hour, with the station now emphasizing currents and recurrents. This marks the fourth attempt by Radio One to compete against long dominant [[WUSL]].<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/108389/boom-praise-swap-locations-in-philadelphia/ Boom 103.9 Philadelphia Segues To Urban Hot AC On New Frequency]</ref>\n\nEight months after WPHI's format switch, [[WISX]] flipped to a classic hip hop-leaning [[rhythmic AC]] on June 30, 2017.\n\nOn December 24, 2019, WPHI rebranded as \"Hip Hop 103.9\".<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/182584/wphi-rebrands-as-hip-hop-103-9/ WPHI Rebrands as Hip Hop 103.9] Radioinsight - December 24, 2019</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[WLIR]] \u2014 the original \"WDRE\" from 1987 to 1996, at 92.7 FM in Garden City, New York\n*[[WXPN-HD2]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{no footnotes|remainder of this section|date=February 2010}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.boomphilly.com/ Boom Philly] &mdash; official WPHI-FM website\n*{{FM station data|WPHI}}\n\n===WDRE era===\n<!-- looks like many of these could be used as references also -->\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bZ9-ELstmjk \"103.9 WDRE Philadelphia, The Birth 1992\"] &mdash; studio footage of \"WIBF\" format to \"WDRE\" format switch at midnight; press parties, including a press event with [[Joey Ramone]]; photos of staff and guests\n*[http://www.xpn.org/yrock-on-xpn/archives/wdre-reunion WDRE Reunion] &mdash; articles and footage about WDRE on the University of Pennsylvania [[WXPN]] website\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20010502162822/http://www.djchas.com/wdrephilly/ WDRE 103.9 FM] &mdash; archived copy of the original WDRE website\n*{{cite news | url = http://citypaper.net/articles/011598/om1.shtml | title = Mourning Show | first = Frank | last = Lewis | work = [[Philadelphia City Paper]] | date = January 15\u201322, 1998 | location = [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]] | access-date = 2010-02-15 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090903192628/http://www.citypaper.net/articles/011598/om1.shtml | archive-date = 2009-09-03 | url-status = dead }} &mdash; follow-up on WDRE popularity after end of format\n*{{cite web | url = http://citypaper.net/articles/013097/article027.shtml | title = Rock On, Please | first = Katherine | last = Kalavritinos | work = [[Philadelphia City Paper]] | date = January 30 \u2013 February 6, 1997 | location = [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]] | access-date = February 15, 2010 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20020917151611/http://citypaper.net/articles/013097/article027.shtml | archive-date = September 17, 2002 | url-status = dead | df = mdy-all }} &mdash; short letter to the editor with WDRE end date given\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090506072710/http://www.angelfire.com/nj2/piratejim/phillyfmhistory2.html Philadelphia FM Radio History] &mdash; timeline of 103.9 <!-- credits sources, and appears to be a source for a some of the text in the article -->\n*[http://www.angelfire.com/nj/NirvanaRulz/wdre/wdre.html 103.9 WDRE...Philly's Modern Rock] &mdash; page on Angelfire, with DJ locations\n\n{{Philadelphia Radio}}\n{{Urban Radio Stations in Pennsylvania}}\n{{Radio One}}\n\n{{coord|40.0416|N|75.2365|W|type:landmark_region:US_source:FCC|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Radio stations established in 1960]]\n[[Category:Urban One stations]]\n[[Category:Radio stations in Philadelphia|PHI-FM]]\n[[Category:1960 establishments in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Urban contemporary radio stations in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Wcquidditch", "label": "safe", "comment": "per the Manual of Style,genres and radio formatsare not capitalized", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WPHI-FM"}
{"title_page": "Zamir White", "text_new": "{{short description|American football running back}}\n{{short description|none}}\n{{Infobox college football player\n|name=Zamir White\n|image=\n|caption=\n|school=Georgia Bulldogs\n|currentnumber=3\n|currentposition=[[Running back]]\n|class={{redshirt}} Sophomore\n|bowlgames=\n*[[2020 Sugar Bowl]]\n|birth_date= \n|birth_place=\n|heightft=6\n|heightin=0\n|weight_lb=215\n|highlights=\n|major=\n|highschool=[[Scotland High School|Scotland]]<br>([[Laurinburg, North Carolina]])\n|pastschools=\n*[[Georgia Bulldogs football|Georgia]] (2018\u2013present)\n|espn=4361777\n}}\n\n'''Zamir White''' is an [[American football]] [[running back]] for the [[Georgia Bulldogs football|Georgia Bulldogs]].\n\n==Early life and high school==\nWhite grew up in [[Laurinburg, North Carolina]] and attended [[Scotland High School]], where he was a member of the football and track teams.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2687081-5-star-rb-zamir-white-commits-to-georgia-over-alabama-ohio-state-unc|title=5-Star RB Zamir White Commits to Georgia over Alabama, Ohio State, UNC|first=Alec|last=Nathan|website=[[Bleacher Report]]|date=June 17, 2017|access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref> As a senior, White rushed for 2,086 yards (14.1 yards per carry) and 34 touchdowns and won the Sam B. Nicola Award as the national high school player of the year before tearing his ACL in the second round of the state playoffs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesfreepress.com/news/sports/college/story/2019/aug/10/georgias-zamir-white-not-lacking-support-retu/500924/|title=Georgia running back Zamir White not lacking for support in return|first=David|last=Paschall|work=[[Chattanooga Times Free Press]]|date=August 10, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.charlotteobserver.com/sports/high-school/article187520943.html|title=Scotland County RB Zamir White wins national player of the year award|first=Langston|last=Wertz Jr.|work=[[The News & Observer]]|date=December 1, 2017|access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://usatodayhss.com/2017/five-star-georgia-rb-commit-zamir-white-tears-acl-in-n-c-playoff-game|title=Five-star Georgia RB commit Zamir White tears ACL in N.C. playoff gam|first=Cam|last=Smith|work=[[USA Today]]|date=November 21, 2017|access-date=April 13, 2020}}</ref> White was a consensus top-five recruit at the running back position and committed to play college football at [[Georgia Bulldogs football|Georgia]] over offers from  [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|Alabama]], [[Clemson Tigers football|Clemson]], [[North Carolina Tar Heels football|North Carolina]] and [[Ohio State Buckeyes football|Ohio State]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbssports.com/college-football/news/top-2018-rusher-zamir-white-commits-to-georgia-continuing-bulldogs-rb-history/|title=Top 2018 rusher Zamir White commits to Georgia, continuing Bulldogs' RB history|first=Ben|last=Kercheval|website=[[CBS Sports]]|date=June 27, 2017|access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\nWhite [[redshirt (college sports)|redshirted]] his true freshman season after suffering a second torn ACL during summer training camp.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/college/georgia/news/zamir-white-underclassmen-likely-to-win-heisman|title=Georgia Football: Zamir White Listed As Underclassman Likely to Win Heisman|first=Brent|last=Wilson|website=[[Sports Illustrated|SI.com]]|date=March 1, 2020|access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.redandblack.com/gameday/zeus-s-coronation-zamir-white-s-journey-back-to-college/article_8abf6a04-c9f1-11e9-b953-9f69aea0d3a6.html|title=Zeus\u2019s coronation: Zamir White\u2019s journey back to college football|first=Myan|last=Patel|work=[[The Red & Black (University of Georgia)|The Red & Black]]|date=August 29, 2019|access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ajc.com/sports/kirby-smart-gives-update-status-bulldogs-zamir-white/O4OYsE58iUXvBvbE9tZpHN/|title=Kirby Smart gives update on status of Bulldogs' Zamir White|work=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|date=April 22, 2019|access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref> White scored the first touchdown of his college career on September 7, 2019 against [[2019 Murray State Racers football team|Murray State]] in an eight carry, 72 yard effort in an 63-17 win.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.savannahnow.com/sports/20190909/georgia-freshmen-pickens-and-white-shine-in-home-debut-for-bulldogs-football-team|title=Georgia freshmen Pickens and White shine in home debut for Bulldogs football team|first=Marc|last=Weiszer|work=[[Savannah Morning News]]|date=September 9, 2019|access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref> He rushed for a season high 92 yards and one touchdown on 18 carries against [[2019 Baylor Bears football team|Baylor]] in the [[2020 Sugar Bowl]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ugawire.usatoday.com/2020/04/07/georgia-bulldogs-football-player-profile-zamir-white/|title=Georgia Bulldogs player profile: RB Zamir White|first=James|last=Morgan|website=UGA Wire|publisher=[[USA Today]]|date=April 7, 2020|access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref> White finished his redshirt freshman season with 408 yards and three touchdowns on 78 carries with two receptions for 20 yards.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://247sports.com/college/georgia/Article/Georgia-football-Zamir-White-breakout-player-ESPN-picks-142442311/|title=ESPN picks Zamir White as Georgia's breakout player in 2020|first=Jake|last=Rowe|website=[[247Sports.com]]|date=January 19, 2020|access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://247sports.com/college/georgia/LongFormArticle/Georgia-Bulldogs-Football-why-Zamir-White-can-be-elite-in-2019-Xs-and-Os--145393831/|title=Xs and Os: Georgia RB Zamir White shows flashes in 2019|first=Jake|last=Rowe|website=[[247Sports.com]]|date=April 11, 2020|access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.laurinburgexchange.com/sports/31925/zamir-for-heisman-scotland-graduate-listed-as-a-2020-candidate|title=Zamir for Heisman? Scotland graduate listed as a 2020 candidate|first=Brian|last=Tester|work=[[Laurinburg Exchange]]|date=December 17, 2019|access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://georgiadogs.com/sports/football/roster/zamir-white/4783 Georgia Bulldogs bio]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:White, Zamir}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American football running backs]]\n[[Category:Georgia Bulldogs football players]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from North Carolina]]\n[[Category:People from Laurinburg, North Carolina]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|none}}\n{{Infobox college football player\n|name=Zamir White\n|image=\n|caption=\n|school=Georgia Bulldogs\n|currentnumber=3\n|currentposition=[[Running back]]\n|class={{redshirt}} Sophomore\n|bowlgames=\n*[[2020 Sugar Bowl]]\n|birth_date= \n|birth_place=\n|heightft=6\n|heightin=0\n|weight_lb=215\n|highlights=\n|major=\n|highschool=[[Scotland High School|Scotland]]<br>([[Laurinburg, North Carolina]])\n|pastschools=\n*[[Georgia Bulldogs football|Georgia]] (2018\u2013present)\n|espn=4361777\n}}\n\n'''Zamir White''' is an [[American football]] [[running back]] for the [[Georgia Bulldogs football|Georgia Bulldogs]].\n\n==Early life and high school==\nWhite grew up in [[Laurinburg, North Carolina]] and attended [[Scotland High School]], where he was a member of the football and track teams.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2687081-5-star-rb-zamir-white-commits-to-georgia-over-alabama-ohio-state-unc|title=5-Star RB Zamir White Commits to Georgia over Alabama, Ohio State, UNC|first=Alec|last=Nathan|website=[[Bleacher Report]]|date=June 17, 2017|access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref> As a senior, White rushed for 2,086 yards (14.1 yards per carry) and 34 touchdowns and won the Sam B. Nicola Award as the national high school player of the year before tearing his ACL in the second round of the state playoffs.<ref>{{cite web|url=